				Final Review
A: Terms （define and describe their content 80 points）
I. Moderate Reform: Zhang Zhidong
1. “Three necessities for China’s survival 
2. The old learning and new learning
II. The Radical Reform: Kang Youwei
3. Kang’s solution of the problem of substance and function.
4. Kang’s major contributions to the modern Chinese thought
5. Kang’s stance toward Confucianism
III. Liang Qichao
6. Renewing people 
7. Private and public morality
8. nationalism vs. culturalism/universalism.
IV. Yen (Yan) Fu and comparative study
9. The sage in the modern West and in the ancient China
10. Preserve faith and/or preserve state/country
11. Yen’s stance to social Darwinism
12. Freedom and reciprocity
13. Individual and society
V. New Culture Movement
14. Its essence and purpose
15. Literary revolution
16. The central question of new traditionalism
VI. Liang Shuming
17. Three needs, three directions, and three cultures
18. The premature of Chinese culture
19. Two features of Chinese culture
VII. Communist Revolution of Mao
20. Peasant rebellion and Communist revolution
21. The form and path of Chinese Communist movement
22. The Democratic, New Democratic, and Socialist Revolution

B: Questions (essays 800--- 1,000 words each)
1. Substance and function in Zhang Zhidong, Kang Youwei, and Yan Fu
2. Kang Youwei’s culturalism and Liang Qichao’s nationalism.
3. Kang Youwei’s effort to make Confucianism as a national religion
4. Criticism of Chinese tradition from Chen Duxiu and Hu Shi.
5. Yen Fu’s major contributions
6. Peasant rebellion and Communist revolution
7. The similarity and difference of the old and new traditionalism
8. The New Culture Movement and Communist Revolution.
9. The path from the Opening to the West and the Communist Revolution






